    <h1>Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Charles Sanders Peirce · 1878 · <a href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Popular_Science_Monthly/Volume_13/August_1878/Illustrations_of_the_Logic_of_Science_VI">Wikisource (public domain)</a><br/><em>Popular Science Monthly</em>, Volume 13, August 1878, pp. 470–482.<br/>Sixth paper in the series "Illustrations of the Logic of Science."</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-200/50 mb-2 font-bold italic">Editor's Summary</p>
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">All reasoning reduces to three forms: deduction applies a rule, induction infers a rule, hypothesis (abduction) infers a case. The bean syllogism. The three modes named.</p>
    </div>

